\begin{document}$$\mu W_{\text{t}} \cos \theta  + W_{\text{c}}  > W_{\text{t}} \sin \theta $$\end{document}

Figure 4a shows a typical result of μ as a function of W. For hard solid surfaces, μ is constant and independent of the load W and contact area A. This is clearly not the case for hairs, especially at low loads. Long ago, it was shown that a variation of μ with W occurs for textiles and fibers (Gralen 1952; Makinson 1952), given by the empirical equation:
